    <title>Combined summary - Is there a tool like Ethereum EVM at present for Bitcoin script?</title>
    <updated>2023-06-15T01:14:18.839114+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2021-August/019352.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>Bitcoin Script programming is primarily based on reverse Polish expression, which can be challenging for some programmers and has affected the promotion of Bitcoin in the technical community. While there is no tool like Ethereum EVM for Bitcoin Script programming, there are higher-level languages such as Miniscript, Min.sc, Simplicity, and Sapio that can compile to Bitcoin Script. Among these, Sapio, written in Rust, may be a good fit for some users.However, it should be noted that these extensions are not currently part of the consensus code and therefore are not widely used. There have been discussions on the bitcoin-dev mailing list on ways to make Bitcoin script programming more accessible and programmer-friendly. Andrew Poelstra of Sapio revealed that the company needs the rust Bitcoin taproot ecosystem to mature before it can take advantage of Taproot with Sapio.He also mentioned the protocol for emulation, which he considers clever. In addition, there have been questions about Sapio and CTV on the Libera equivalents of Freenode channels #sapio and ##ctv-bip-review over the past months. It is unclear whether Sapio plans to join and claim those channels.In response to a recent post on an online forum that sought information about a tool similar to Ethereum EVM that allows users to write Bitcoin scripts in a syntax similar to Python or other programming languages and translate them into original bitcoin scripts, Gijs van Dam suggested using higher-level languages like Miniscript, Min.sc, Simplicity, or Sapio, which all compile to Bitcoin Script.While discussing Sapio's plans to take advantage of Taproot, Michael Folkson asked about updating the "No Taproot" section of the Sapio docs. Poelstra replied that Sapio assumes extensions, but if they are not present, they can be stubbed out with a signing federation. He further stated that the protocol for emulation is designed to ensure that contract compilation is completely offline and the oracles are stateless. Relevant links to learn more about the CTV emulator and finish options are provided.</summary>
